snippet.textDisplay: I 100% believe you can be a strong independent woman that don't need no man (ahh the grammar there makes me cringe) while actually having said man.  There is a pretty large age gap between my boyfriend and me (7 years) and to be honest, I think our relationship works so well because he sees me as an equal. He knows that I don't need him and that I am with him because I want to be.  We currently live 10 hours apart and have done so off and on for the last 2 years of our relationship. We talk every day on the phone; most of the time for less than 3 mins for "his surprise call" he calls says he loves me hoping I am having a good day and learning a lot and that we will chat later. However, most of the time it's like I am single. I do everything by myself and I have learned to love that. We are our own separate individuals who have our own dreams and goals in life. The only difference is we want to share our experiences with each other and watch each other grow into the best versions of ourselves.

snippet.textDisplay:
I never really felt the pressure to be in a relationship. I'm 26 and I've only had one relationship, and I definitely prefer to be single.

I like my freedom and not having to consider someone else when I make decisions. I can go wherever I want, do whatever I want, and don't have to plan around their wants and needs.

I have one or two friends who have jumped from long-term relationship to long-term relationship, and they've done this since we were 15. It's been 10+ years and most of that they've spent being someone's girlfriend. They don't really know how to be alone because they're always in a serious relationship with someone.

As far as pressure from family goes, my family don't really care, I don't ever remember them pressuring me for grandkids or to get a boyfriend/husband. They never really brought up marriage as something that was expected of me.

I find it very easy to ignore societal pressure. If society is telling you "get a boyfriend, get married, have a baby!" and you don't want to do that, just mark it down as 'Not Applicable' and go and do what you want. Problem solved 👍

snippet.textDisplay: I agree about being pressured into a relationship so young.  Every time I go to any family reunions, my aunts always ask me if I have a boyfriend or any boys I'm eyeing.  This feels like pressure to me.  I'm 19 and my last relationship was a year and a half ago.  I don't pressure myself to get into a relationship because I honestly love being single and I think I've grown to learn what I like and don't like in a guy based on my one long-term relationship and the few dates I went on afterward.  For example, I know that I want someone around my age, doing similar things like going to college, and with a goal in mind and determination to pursue that goal.  And if I don't find anyone that's perfect for me until I'm 35-40, then I'm fine with adopting. :)

I’m 15 (boy) and I’ve never been in a relationship before. Confusion of my sexuality aside, I was in a FUCKING rush two years ago. When I was 13, I literally looked for “which girl I’ve known that are single and I wouldn’t hate to have for a girlfriend? XX suits! Let’s chase her!” And then I’ll chase her until I failed or gave up. One of the reason I would do this is because of peer pressure. When I was in form 2, having a boyfriend/girlfriend is ~cool~. Also, another reason I want to have a girlfriend so bad is that I want to have someone ~be with me~ all the time to cover the fact that I don’t have any friends. (Which is another problem)

Now, I already acknowledged that what I used to do is FUCKING CREEPY and dating just because I want to date someone is wrong 😇 I’ll just wait for the right girl (or boy??) to show up and Until then, I’m happy to be single!

snippet.textDisplay:
A few words of wisdom from an old man:

1. No one really has any idea “who they are”.
2. No one knows what they want to do with their life, where their life is headed, what they’ll accomplish in the future. Everyone is taking it one day at a time walking blindly into the future.
3. Everyone is miserable, lonely, and worried. Everyone is depressed, everyone is struggling. Thing is, everyone is putting forth a decent effort to keep their “happy mask” on and trying one day at a time to keep their chin above the waterline as far as mental and emotional health goes.
4. Everyone wants friends, everyone wants a significant other, just that no one really knows what to look for, where to meet anyone, and they don’t want to take the time and effort to get past the initial stage of getting to know the person so as to find out if the person in question is awesome or not. All you can do is just live your life and get to know people as they interact with you.
5. The grass isn’t greener on the other side of the fence. Sometimes it’s greener because there’s a septic system underneath. Some of the most miserable and isolated people I’ve ever known are married people. They get married, distance themselves from their friends, they stop taking time for themselves, they don’t maintain their own personal sense of identity and they get really tired of the person their with and all they want is to go back to how things were before they got married.
6. The best way to go about life is one day at a time and to just try your best to be okay with the way your life is right now. Set goals, work towards them, have hobbies, have a couple good friends, do stuff outside the apartment, and just maintain your own identity. Take it one day at a time and your life will play out however it plays out.

snippet.textDisplay: I have been in a relationship for almost 6 years with my boyfriend from high school and I still really felt this video. During the first years of our relationship (in high school), I was really struggling with self-esteem and I relied very heavily on my bf to get a sense of self-worth. Now that I am a junior in college, I really feel that I am independent and our relationship is much healthier because my bf has helped me see that I am a cool fucking person who is whole on my own. Now I'm trying to figure out what I really want to do, and who I really want to me and I feel very lucky that I have a very supportive, kind partner in my life who pushes me to work on myself for myself. In bouts of anxiety, I find myself questioning if I'm messing up my college years by being in a monogamous relationship and not having the experience of hookup culture. or going on dates. This video really reminded me that whether in a relationship or not, struggles with identity and self-esteem/worth happen to all of us and our romantic relationships are not what make or break how wonderful we are, or how much we have to offer the world as individuals.

I'm 23 years-old and feel extremely related to this video, last year I moved to a different country and I felt so lonely that I was about dropping everything (school, career opportunities) to become my boyfriends' housewife. Not, that being a housewife is something bad, but for me, it came from such a desperate mindset, I just didn't feel comfortable being alone, and I had several break downs just facing the idea of having to live my life by my own.
This Valentine's day I went to the movies by myself to watch "Parasites" (great movie, by the way, I would love to hear your thoughts about it) and it was definitely weird, the taxi who drive me there, the lady who handed me the ticket, the guy selling popcorns all of them had this surprise and also judgemental face when I asked a ticket for one, or just one combo of popcorn... However, I felt so glad I went by my self, I'm always waiting for my friends or boyfriend to do stuff but they don't like drama movies, don't have time, whatever excuse. It felt great just go and do things that I like.

snippet.textDisplay: I recently feel pressured over not having a serious relationship since im 23 this year. Most of my friends are in a serious relationship and they talk about marriage already. In my country, women usually get married at the age of 25-27ish. One of my guy friend even told me that when I hit the age of 27 and still single, i have to go on "sale" so i won't die alone. I honestly feel good about being single before, but hearing those things and the peer pressure, I feel so bad and so sad. I even begin to question my self worth and been too stupid that i cling on a guy that feeds on my insecurities. I let him use me to boost his ego just so he won't leave me. But hearing you say all these things make me feel so much better, Ashley! So thank you. I'll be more confident and say fuck you to all the people that brings negativity in my life and take time for myself to decide what I actually want in life, not what others decide my life should be.

snippet.textDisplay:
I am 21 as well and i have yet to get over my fear of aging and failing in life. I try to do what i want and travel but the fear that i will be 30 and a failure is so engraved in me that it makes me sad. What if i don't succeed in my field and what if i end up sticking to a job that just pays rent but doesn't fulfill me? And the perception of life basically being over after you turn 30 has affected me so much because i know in my heart it is not true and i feel like the fear of aging is basically a fear of dying which i think is a normal fear to have, but it takes away from enjoying my life since i end up always thinking where i am going to be in a couple of years and what i should be doing that i forget to think about what i should be enjoying and doing now.


p.s. reading all the comments and realizing that a lot of peoples brains are just always on overdrive makes me feel a little better about my own brain never shutting up.

snippet.textDisplay:
I love that you love the comments on these videos! I've been on this binge recently of rewatching chick flicks from my childhood and it's crazy how problematic some (okay...most) of them are!

I've been more attracted to cool, unconventionally attractive (or just unattractive) guys but when I got out of an (emotionally abusive) 5 yeah relationship I did a crazy amount of tinder dating with a lot of those hot but crazy guys! And right when I decided I was done with it I met my current boyfriend and I think we still have a healthy relationship. Which I love!

On the other hand, I never really learned to be single. I was a serial monogamist and even in the year I was single and tried out polyamory I think I mostly did it to just constantly have a relationship. I don't know how to deal with it.

I also have a friend who's 30+ (and me as a young 24 yo) and I admire her independence but even she seems relationships. God life is tough. That's just it!

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm 21 and never had a relationship and sometimes I realize that many people find that weird because they had their first relationship in their teens. Also in all those movies, it's such a big deal to find love while you're young. And also when it comes to virginity, it seems like a big deal to "loose" it as soon as possible.
But on the other hand I don't really think about it that much cause to me it's normal to be single and I don't wanna do things I'm not 100% sure about. And yes i also feel pressured and feel kinda unnormal but I won't hang out with people who judge me for that anyway.

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm in a long-term relationship (for me at least) of almost 3 years and I often have the urge to break up with my boyfriend because I don't feel like settling down yet and have beautiful FOMO... I can't imagine that he could be the last man I have ever had a first kiss or a first touch with while I'm only 22.

I really enjoyed being single as relationships cost so much energy even though it's easy sailing. I really like my boyfriend and oftentimes I'm afraid that my feelings come from a place of uncertainty and discontent with my current situation and I'd like to change the thing that would be the easiest (but oh so hurtful) to change. I feel like, even though he doesn't expect it from me or doesn't ask for much I make decisions based on the relationship I'm in and I feel like I limit myself because I have to take care of it..

I just wish I would have met him maybe 5 years later so I could enjoy being and living just for myself a little longer.
